<paragraph blockId="11.[140,1108,1363,1672]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">
moths differ greatly in appearance and size; however most species tend to be some combination of white and gray, the white tending to be shiny. Th e forewing tends to be broad, often with a rounded apex. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[370,531,1433,1460]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(Figs 30–34). All of the species have a well-developed, setose ampulla on the clasper and the clasper is usually weakly sclerotized except for a spinelike apex. In many species the costal part of the valve is more heavily sclerotized than the ventral part. Th e vesica in the New World species is elongated and without diverticula or spiny areas, except for a long, tapered, horn-like subapical diverticulum that is covered with minute denticles so that it appears to function as an enlarged cornutus; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hufnagel" authorityYear="1766" box="[948,1100,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="148" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucida">
<emphasis box="[948,1100,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Acontia lucida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the type-species from western Eurasia, has a spinulose subbasal diverticulum with a spiny
</paragraph>
