<paragraph blockId="12.[140,1108,1363,1672]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
apex, as well as the false cornutus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[506,690,1363,1389]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(Fig. 44). These consist of an elongate, sclerotized, ostium bursae, a tubular, membranous ductus bursae, and an oval membranous corpus bursae with the ductus seminalis at the anterior end. In Old World 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ochsenheimer" authorityYear="1816" box="[931,1010,1434,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[931,1010,1434,1460]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Acontia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are separate sclerotized plates in the ostium and ductus bursae and the ductus seminalis is at the end of a sclerotized appendix bursae, which is on the posterior left side of the corpus bursae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[140,1108,1363,1672]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,338,1539,1565]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis box="[185,246,1539,1565]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" reason="1">Food</emphasis>
plants.
</emphasis>
The food plants are recorded in the New World only for an undescribed species related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grote &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1870" box="[459,565,1575,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretata">
<emphasis box="[459,476,1575,1601]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[493,565,1575,1600]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">cretata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that occurs in Texas and northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1016,1103,1575,1601]" name="Mexico" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Mexico</collectingCountry>
; it has been reared from 
<taxonomicName authority="Kunth" authorityName="Kunth" authorityYear="1822" box="[416,734,1610,1636]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Abutilon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pedunculare">
<emphasis box="[416,652,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Abutilon pedunculare</emphasis>
Kunth
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[751,875,1610,1637]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malvaceae</taxonomicName>
). In the Old World, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hufnagel" authorityYear="1766" box="[140,297,1645,1671]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acontia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucida">
<emphasis box="[140,297,1645,1671]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Acontia lucida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
feeds primarily, but not exclusively, on species of 
<taxonomicName box="[858,979,1645,1671]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malvaceae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
